\newpage

\subsection*{Abstract}\label{abstract}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Abstract}

Small datasets with intercorrelated predictors pose serious challenges
to Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) regression, often producing coefficients
that are statistically unstable and economically implausible. A
motivating example in cost estimation is the learning curve with rate
effect, where lot midpoint correlates with lot size as production ramps
up, and domain knowledge establishes that learning and rate slopes
should be \(\leq 100\%\).

This paper combines penalized regularization (Lasso, Ridge, Elastic Net)
with constrained optimization to ensure economically valid coefficients
while maintaining predictive accuracy. Through a Monte Carlo simulation
study of 8,100 scenarios using quantity profiles randomly selected from
Selected Acquisition Reports (SARs) with simulated average unit costs at
varying coefficients of variation, we find that Penalized-Constrained
Regression with GCV selection (PCReg-GCV) outperforms OLS in predictive
accuracy, with the strongest advantage precisely when OLS produces
economically unreasonable coefficients.

\textbf{Key Findings:}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  PCReg-GCV provides better out-of-sample predictions even when OLS
  produces reasonable coefficients
\item
  OLS with learning variable only (OLS-LearnOnly) performs poorly
  outside the training range
\item
  Constraints introduce beneficial bias that improves extrapolation
\item
  Generalized Cross-Validation (GCV) enables stable hyperparameter
  selection with as few as 5 observations
\end{itemize}

The research team developed the \texttt{penalized-constrained} Python
package specifically for the cost estimating community after finding no
existing library that combined these capabilities.

\subsubsection{Methodological
Foundation}\label{methodological-foundation}

The objective function minimized by PCReg combines a loss function with
regularization penalties subject to coefficient bounds:

\[
\min_{\theta} \underbrace{\sum_{i=1}^{n} L(y_i, \hat{y}_i)}_{\text{Loss (e.g., SSPE)}} + \underbrace{\alpha \left[ \rho \|\theta\|_1 + \frac{1-\rho}{2} \|\theta\|_2^2 \right]}_{\text{Elastic Net Penalty}}
\]

subject to:
\(\theta_{\text{lower}} \leq \theta \leq \theta_{\text{upper}}\)

where \(\alpha\) controls penalty strength and \(\rho\) balances L1
(Lasso) vs L2 (Ridge) regularization.

\textbf{Bounds can be loose or tight:}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Loose bounds} (e.g., 70-100\%): Allow flexibility while
  preventing egregious violations
\item
  \textbf{Tight bounds} (e.g., 85-95\%): Incorporate strong prior
  knowledge but risk over-constraining
\end{itemize}

Research foundations include James, Paulson, and Rusmevichientong (2020)
demonstrating that constrained Lasso can achieve optimal prediction
under monotonicity assumptions, and classical Ridge regression theory
showing that some bias can reduce overall mean squared error when
predictors are correlated.

\newpage

\subsection{Introduction}\label{introduction}

Developing Cost Estimating Relationships (CERs) for small datasets (5-30
data points), a recurring pattern emerges: strong fit statistics (R²,
CV) but nonsensical coefficients---wrong signs, implausible magnitudes,
and poor p-values for critical predictors. As Department of Defense
analysts, this story may feel all too familiar.

Multicollinear datasets are a frequent presence in cost analysis,
causing models to misbehave. The consequences of multicollinearity in
small samples are well-documented (Flynn and James 2016):

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Unstable coefficient estimates}: Coefficients swing wildly
  with small data changes
\item
  \textbf{Wrong coefficient signs}: Estimates flip positive/negative
  contrary to domain knowledge
\item
  \textbf{Unreliable hypothesis testing}: High F-statistic but
  individually insignificant t-statistics
\item
  \textbf{Inflated variance}: Coefficient variance increases by factor
  \(1/(1-R^2)\) where \(R^2\) is the correlation between predictors
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{The Learning Curve
Problem}\label{the-learning-curve-problem}

The motivating example for this research is the learning curve with rate
effect:

\begin{equation}\phantomsection\label{eq-learning-curve}{
Y = T_1 \cdot (\text{LotMidpoint})^b \cdot (\text{LotQuantity})^c \cdot \varepsilon
}\end{equation}

where:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \(T_1\) = theoretical first unit cost
\item
  \(b\) = learning slope (learning rate = \(2^b\), typically 70-95\%)
\item
  \(c\) = rate slope (rate effect = \(2^c\), typically 70-95\%)
\item
  \(\varepsilon\) = multiplicative error
\end{itemize}

In this specification, lot midpoint (learning variable) is inherently
correlated with lot size (rate variable) as production ramps up. Domain
knowledge establishes that learning and rate slopes should be
\(\leq 100\%\)---costs should not \emph{increase} with cumulative
production experience.

\subsubsection{Research Contribution}\label{research-contribution}

This paper provides a practical guide combining penalized regularization
with constrained optimization for cost estimation:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Python package} combining Elastic Net penalties with
  coefficient bound constraints
\item
  \textbf{GCV framework} for hyperparameter selection without data
  splitting
\item
  \textbf{Simulation benchmarks} comparing PCReg-GCV against OLS across
  varying sample sizes
\item
  \textbf{Practical decision rules} for when to use constrained methods
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{Model Diagnostics}\label{model-diagnostics}

The \texttt{penalized-constrained} package provides comprehensive
diagnostics for assessing model fit quality, including bootstrap
confidence intervals that compare constrained vs unconstrained
estimation.

\textbf{Generalized Degrees of Freedom (GDF)}

For constrained models, computing proper degrees of freedom requires
special consideration. When constraints are \emph{binding} (coefficients
at bounds), those parameters effectively lose freedom. We use the Gaines
et al.~(2018) formula:

\[
\text{df} = |\text{Active predictors}| - |\text{Binding inequality constraints}|
\]

For this model:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  GDF (gaines): 3.0
\item
  Active constraints: 0
\item
  Binding constraints: None
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Bootstrap Analysis: Constrained vs Unconstrained}

preventing full exploration of parameter space). \{\#tbl-bootstrap\}

\textbf{Key Diagnostic Insights:}

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \textbf{Constraints at bounds}: When bootstrap samples frequently hit
  the constraint boundaries, this indicates the data is ``pulling''
  towards values outside the feasible region---exactly when constraints
  provide the most benefit.
\item
  \textbf{CI width changes}: Constrained CIs may be \emph{narrower}
  (constraints reduce parameter uncertainty) or \emph{wider} (bounds
  truncate the natural distribution). Both patterns are informative
  about how constraints interact with the data.
\item
  \textbf{Unconstrained bootstrap divergence}: Large differences between
  constrained and unconstrained bootstrap means indicate the constraints
  are actively shaping the solution---the model would produce very
  different (and likely implausible) coefficients without them.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Note on nonlinear optimization}: PCReg uses numerical
optimization (scipy's SLSQP or trust-constr), which means some classical
regression assumptions (closed-form solutions, exact t-statistics) don't
directly apply. Bootstrap provides a robust alternative for inference
that doesn't rely on these assumptions.

\subsection{Simulation Study}\label{simulation-study}

To systematically evaluate when PCReg-GCV outperforms OLS, we conducted
a Monte Carlo simulation study with 8,100 scenarios.

\subsubsection{Data Generation}\label{data-generation}

For each scenario, we:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Randomly selected a quantity profile} from the SAR database
  (actual defense program procurement histories)
\item
  \textbf{Generated simulated average unit costs} using the learning
  curve model (Equation~\ref{eq-learning-curve}) with the scenario's
  true parameters
\item
  \textbf{Added multiplicative lognormal noise} with the specified
  coefficient of variation (CV)
\item
  \textbf{Split data}: First \(n\) lots for training, remaining lots for
  test
\end{enumerate}

This approach ensures realistic lot structures (varying quantities,
realistic ramp-up patterns) while controlling the true underlying
parameters. Note that the number of test lots varies by scenario
depending on the program's total lot history---some programs have many
available lots beyond training, others have few. This variability is
acceptable as it reflects real-world conditions.

\subsection{Key Findings}\label{key-findings}

\subsubsection{Finding 1: PCReg-GCV Outperforms OLS Regardless of
Coefficient
Reasonableness}\label{finding-1-pcreg-gcv-outperforms-ols-regardless-of-coefficient-reasonableness}

A key finding is that PCReg-GCV provides better out-of-sample
predictions \textbf{even when OLS produces reasonable coefficients}.

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}lrr@{}}
\caption{PCReg-GCV win rates against OLS by coefficient

\subsubsection{Finding 2: OLS-LearnOnly Performs Poorly Outside Training
Range}\label{finding-2-ols-learnonly-performs-poorly-outside-training-range}

OLS with only the learning variable (OLS-LearnOnly) ignores the rate
effect, which leads to poor extrapolation:

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}lr@{}}
\caption{Average Test MAPE by
model}\label{tbl-mape-comparison}\tabularnewline

OLS-LearnOnly & 15.9\% \\
OLS & 9.9\% \\
PCReg-GCV & 7.7\% \\
\end{longtable}

OLS-LearnOnly has worse Test MAPE than full OLS in \textbf{63.9\%} of
scenarios. While simplifying the model may seem appealing, omitting the
rate effect leads to systematic prediction errors outside the training
range.

\textbf{Key Insight}: While OLS is theoretically unbiased (mean errors
near 0), it has high variance---the distribution is wide. PCReg-GCV may
have slight bias but much lower variance, leading to better overall
prediction accuracy (the classic bias-variance tradeoff).

\subsection{Recommendations: When to Use
PCReg-GCV}\label{recommendations-when-to-use-pcreg-gcv}

We trained a decision tree to identify conditions where PCReg-GCV is
most beneficial, using only features available to practitioners (not
true parameter values):

\begin{figure}

\centering{

\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio]{penalized_constrained_regression_files/figure-pdf/fig-decision-tree-output-1.pdf}}

}

\caption{\label{fig-decision-tree}Decision tree for model selection.
Green nodes favor PCReg-GCV; orange nodes favor OLS. The tree uses only
information available to the analyst.}

\end{figure}%

\textbf{Practical Decision Rules:}

Based on the decision tree and simulation analysis:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{If OLS produces unreasonable coefficients} (LC or RC outside
  70-100\%): \textbf{Use PCReg-GCV}
\item
  \textbf{If sample size ≤ 10 lots}: \textbf{Prefer PCReg-GCV} (more
  stable)
\item
  \textbf{If predictor correlation \textgreater{} 0.9}: \textbf{Prefer
  PCReg-GCV} (multicollinearity protection)
\item
  \textbf{Otherwise}: Either method acceptable, but PCReg-GCV still
  slightly favored
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Conclusions}\label{conclusions}

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{PCReg-GCV improves out-of-sample prediction} even when OLS
  produces reasonable coefficients
\item
  \textbf{Constraints introduce beneficial bias} that reduces prediction
  variance
\item
  \textbf{OLS-LearnOnly performs poorly} outside the training
  range---don't oversimplify
\item
  \textbf{GCV enables reliable hyperparameter selection} with as few as
  5 training observations
\item
  \textbf{Simple decision rule}: When in doubt, use PCReg-GCV; the
  downside is minimal
\end{enumerate}

\section{Appendix A: Simulation Details}\label{sec-appendix-simulation}

\subsection{Data Generation Process}\label{data-generation-process}

For each of the 8,100 scenarios:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Select quantity profile}: Randomly sample a defense program
  from the SAR database with sufficient lot history
\item
  \textbf{Extract lot structure}: Use actual procurement quantities and
  calculate lot midpoints
\item
  \textbf{Generate true costs}: Apply learning curve model with scenario
  parameters
\item
  \textbf{Add noise}: Multiply true costs by lognormal error:
  \(Y_{obs} = Y_{true} \cdot e^{\epsilon}\) where
  \(\epsilon \sim N(-\sigma^2/2, \sigma^2)\)
\item
  \textbf{Split data}: First \(n\) lots for training, \textbf{all
  remaining lots} for test (variable test set size)
\end{enumerate}
